(42, 15, 30, 2, 32, 11, 11, NULL, 'Themes of Rebellion and Forgiveness', 'This connection highlights themes of rebellion against authority and the subsequent plea for mercy. In both passages, there is a focus on the consequences of actions and the desire for reconciliation after wrongdoing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 15, 30, 42, 15, 22, 23, 'killed for him the fatted calf', 'Celebration of the Prodigal Son', 'Both passages emphasize the act of killing the fatted calf as a celebration of the son''s return. This connection highlights the father''s joy and forgiveness towards his wayward son.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 15, 31, 41, 7, 27, 28, NULL, 'Connection of Provision and Belonging', 'This connection highlights the theme of belonging and provision. In Luke, the son is assured that all the father has is his, while in Mark, the woman acknowledges that even the dogs receive crumbs, indicating a shared access to sustenance.', 'theme', 0.356, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 15, 31, 45, 9, 4, 4, 'all that I have is thine', 'Inheritance and Belonging', 'This connection highlights the theme of belonging and inheritance. In Luke, the son is assured that all the father''s possessions are his, paralleling how Romans emphasizes the Israelites'' privileged status as God''s chosen people with the promises and covenants.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 15, 31, 40, 20, 13, 16, 'all that I have is thine', 'God''s Generosity and Fairness', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of God''s generosity and the idea that all that He has belongs to His followers. The phrase ''all that I have is thine'' in Luke reflects the same spirit of fairness and abundance seen in the parable of the laborers in Matthew, where the owner gives equally to all workers.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 15, 31, 45, 11, 1, 1, 'all that I have is thine', 'Connection of Belonging and Identity', 'This connection highlights the theme of belonging and identity within God''s family. In Luke, the son is assured of his place and inheritance, while in Romans, Paul emphasizes his identity as part of God''s chosen people.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 15, 31, 42, 19, 22, 23, 'all that I have is thine', 'Servanthood and Responsibility', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between the master and his servants. In Luke 15:31, the son is assured of his inheritance, while in Luke 19:22-23, the servant is judged for not using what was entrusted to him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 15, 32, 42, 15, 24, 24, 'was dead, and is alive again; and was lost, and is found.', 'Rejoicing Over the Lost Found', 'Both passages emphasize the joy of reconciliation, stating that the son was ''dead'' and is ''alive again,'' and that he was ''lost'' and is ''found.'' This connection highlights the theme of celebration in response to redemption.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 15, 32, 49, 2, 1, 10, 'was dead, and is alive again', 'Connection of Life and Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being ''dead'' and then ''alive'' again. Luke 15:32 speaks of a brother who was dead and is now alive, while Ephesians 2:1-10 discusses being quickened from death in sins to life in Christ. This connection highlights the transformative power of grace.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 15, 32, 23, 35, 10, 10, 'make merry, and be glad', 'Joy and Restoration Connection', 'Both passages emphasize joy and gladness following a restoration. Luke speaks of a brother who was lost and found, while Isaiah describes the ransomed returning with joy, indicating a theme of renewal and celebration.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 15, 32, 19, 51, 8, 8, 'make merry, and be glad', 'Joy and Restoration Connection', 'This connection highlights the themes of joy and restoration in both passages. Luke 15:32 speaks of rejoicing over a brother who was lost and found, while Psalms 51:8 expresses a desire for joy and gladness after brokenness.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 15, 32, 45, 3, 4, 4, 'was lost, and is found', 'Connection of Justification and Redemption', 'This connection highlights the themes of being ''found'' and justified. Both passages emphasize the transformation from a state of loss to one of life and righteousness.', 'theme', 0.363, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 15, 32, 32, 4, 10, 11, 'was lost, and is found', 'Theme of Redemption and Mercy', 'This connection highlights the themes of redemption and mercy found in both passages. In Luke, the joy of a brother being found parallels God''s compassion for Nineveh, emphasizing the value of lost souls being restored.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 15, 32, 45, 15, 9, 13, 'make merry, and be glad', 'Joy and Rejoicing Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of joy in response to salvation and reconciliation. Luke 15:32 speaks of making merry for the brother who was lost and is found, while Romans 15:9-13 calls for rejoicing among the Gentiles for God''s mercy.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 1, 60, 4, 10, 10, 'steward; and the same was accused', 'Stewardship and Accountability', 'This connection highlights the theme of stewardship in both passages. The rich man’s steward is accused of wasting goods, while 1 Peter emphasizes being good stewards of grace.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 1, 40, 25, 14, 30, 'wasted his goods', 'Stewardship and Accountability', 'This connection highlights the theme of stewardship and accountability in both passages. In Luke, the steward is accused of wasting goods, while in Matthew, servants are rewarded or punished based on how they manage their master''s resources.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 1, 42, 12, 42, 42, 'steward', 'Connection of Stewardship Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the role of a steward, highlighting the importance of faithfulness and responsibility in managing one''s duties. The rich man in Luke 16:1 is contrasted with the faithful steward in Luke 12:42, illustrating the consequences of stewardship.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 1, 46, 4, 1, 2, 'steward; and the same was accused', 'Stewardship and Faithfulness', 'This connection highlights the theme of stewardship in both passages. The steward in Luke is accused of wasting goods, while Paul emphasizes the requirement for stewards to be found faithful in 1 Corinthians.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 1, 59, 4, 3, 3, 'wasted his goods', 'Stewardship and Misuse of Resources', 'This connection highlights the theme of mismanagement of resources. In Luke, the steward is accused of wasting goods, while in James, asking amiss reflects a misuse of what one seeks.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 1, 56, 1, 7, 7, 'steward', 'Stewardship and Accountability', 'This connection highlights the theme of stewardship and accountability in both passages. The rich man’s steward in Luke is accused of wasting goods, while Titus emphasizes the qualities expected of a steward of God, including being blameless and not self-willed.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 1, 42, 15, 13, 13, 'wasted his goods', 'Wasting Wealth Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''wasting'' resources. The steward in Luke 16:1 is accused of wasting the rich man''s goods, while the younger son in Luke 15:13 wastes his substance with riotous living.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 2, 9, 2, 23, 24, 'give an account of thy stewardship', 'Accountability in Stewardship', 'This connection highlights the theme of accountability for one''s actions. Both passages emphasize the need for individuals in positions of responsibility to give an account of their conduct, reflecting the consequences of their stewardship.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 16, 2, 21, 11, 9, 10, NULL, 'Judgment and Accountability Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of accountability before God. Both passages emphasize the necessity of giving an account for one''s actions, whether in stewardship or in the enjoyment of youth.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
